content.description: One crux move down low leads to excellent sustained climbing on excellent rock and good movement.  Well worth the extra little hike.
content.protection: 6 Bolts will get you to the fixed anchors and your rappel.
content.location: This is the first route at the High Life area and is next to two other moderate routes.  This section of cliff is about 100 feet left of the mail High Life Wall and right behind some trees.  Route # 1 in the High Life section of the guidebook.

content.description: 3rd bolted line on the main section of High Life Wall with thin pocket bulge below second bolt.
content.location: Right of Topeka and Sell your Soles. Left of the start of Always Smooth, The High Life, and Never Bitter.

content.description: chossy. Climb up to the small right facing corner.
content.location: To the right of Party Foul.

content.description: Okay route with some thin moves. Climb up to a small broken roof.
content.location: Right of Last Swag and left of Life is Good.

content.description: The crux is moving past the third bolt.  Small right hand crimp (a bit of a crank to reach located at about one-o'clock); slap the arete with your left and find the key left foot placement to finish the move.  I enjoyed this route!  Fun, with cool balance moves on the bottom section.  The upper section has buckets.
content.protection: Bolted; 7 bolts with two shut anchor.
content.location: On an obvious arete; the first climb you reach on your left, 30 meters past Walk in the Park and the two eights.

content.description: Another great High Life wall moderate that is similar to the other two routes on this wall with an additional "mini-tower" feature to finish the route on.  Not really a crux, just good, fun, sustained casual movement.
content.protection: 7 Bolts will find you at the fixed anchors and a big smile on your mug. :)
content.location: This third route right on the section of wall and 5 feet right of "Looking Sharp".

content.description: Deidre Burton and Jim Steagall's Climbing book recommends stick clipping 1st bolt.
content.location: It is located around the corner of Hands of Chaos 5.13a/b arete, which is right of Hang 'Em High, and it has only 4 bolts.

content.description: Tough moves on steep, strange rock leads to difficult,thin and technical moves. Guide book has always shown this as 12a but I think it is much harder than High Life or even Never Bitter. Really cool climb that doesn't get enough attention.
content.location: 2nd route from left on this wall, between Topeka and the High Life trio.
Far right of Cream Stout on a different section of wall. Climb the face and left of the middle of the roof.

content.description: The same start as "The High Life" then traverses right at the 6th bolt. 9 bolts
Maybe the best route on this section of the wall; a thin section down low leads to pockets and jugs up higher.  Great route that is not to be missed.
content.protection: Well protected sport route with 6 bolts to fixed anchors and your rappel.
content.location: 5 feet right of "Walk in the Park" and the center route on this section of the wall.  Look for the bolts and you can't miss it.

content.description: I found the crux to be clipping and passing the second bolt.  Nice climbing for the first 40 feet or so.  Then, well, not as compelling.
content.location: This is the farthest right climb on the High Life wall (as listed in Burton and Steagall (1997)

content.description: Climb the face and finish right of the roof.
content.location: Two climbs right of Party Foul and two climbs left of Life is Good.

content.description: Fun climbing that gets steeper as you climb.  Thin, cruxy section fairly low leads to a mounting pump.
content.location: Right end of High Life Wall, just left of "Life is Good."

content.description: This is certainly one of the most fun climbs of the grade at Jacks.  It starts with an excellent 5.11- section that moves into a featured flake where you can rest for as long as you want.  The bolts fork above this, The High Life is the center line.  Climb through the roof and finish on some 5.10 that feels pretty desperate if you're pumped.
content.protection: 9 bolts to a two bolt anchor
content.location: In the center of the High Life Wall. Look for the pocketed flake halfway up the route.

content.description: Pull the standard overhung Jack's roof start to pull onto the face, then make a tricky move to a good hold and the second bolt.  Continue up with a few difficult sections to a few final hard moves pulling the last roof below the anchors.  Could be a bit soft for the 12a grade.
content.location: Right side of the Main "High Life" wall.  To the left is "Always Smooth" and the routes that share that start.  To the Right on the arete is "Hands of Chaos"

content.description: A couple bouldery moves off the deck lead to a long face with multiple cruxes and great sustained climbing at the grade. This one builds the pump and keeps it coming! Watch out for some potentially loose flakes.
content.protection: 9 cold shuts to two shut anchor.
content.location: Third route to the right on the "main wall" at High Life. Go left when the line splits at the third bolt (the bolt lines that cut right are 5.12).

content.description: This route was in the book but not on mountainproject and I haven't climbed it yet but look forward to it. I gave it a 2 star just to be fair and will adjust the rating later.
content.location: This climb is the second climb right of Silver Bullet and just right of a climb called Micro Brew.

content.description: Excellent area to get away from the crowds on weekends.  This wall is the furthest developed wall away from the mail trail and past the Cracker Jack Cliffs.  Rock quality and routes are excellent with a lot of harder lines but 3 or 4 moderates that are worth the hike alone.  The routes tend to be a bit longer than most Jacks Canyon routes as a bonus.  This area gets shade in the mornings and late afternoons.
